[
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition of #mv_polynomial.degrees looks very strange to me, at least I had never encountered it in mathematics.<br>\nIt defines, for example, the degrees of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> P = x^2y+y^3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> to be the multiset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{x,x,y,y,y\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> whose product gives <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x^2y^3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, a least common multiple of the monomials that appear in the polynomial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>From the perspective of computer algebra, I would have imagined that the degrees of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> would be either <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{x^2y,y^3\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{ (2,1), (0,3)\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{(</span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mclose\">)}</span></span></span></span>, the set of (uncoefficiented) monomials or of exponents.</p>\n<p>What is the reason it was introduced in this way?</p>",
        "id": 311991887,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1669288582
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What would you expect the degree of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P = x^2y + y^3 + y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> to be?</p>",
        "id": 311999819,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1669291344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(also, you need <code>docs</code> before the <code>#</code> for the link to work)</p>",
        "id": 311999862,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1669291362
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are many degrees available, the three obvious ones are the degree with respect to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> (2 in this case),  the one with respect to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> (3), or the total degree (3 as well). But you can assign weights to variables and you get many other, of a similar vein. </p>\n<p>These degrees do not give rise to a total ordering of monomials, and the theory of Gröbner bases proposes that you fix a total ordering of the monomials, and then the degree would be the exponent of the highest monomial.<br>\nOne way to get such an ordering consists in fixing weights which are linearly independent over Q, and taking the degree then. But the lexicographic orderings, or their opposite, are also pretty much studied. (So the degree could be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x^2y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> if you take the variables in the standard order, or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y^3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0085em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> if you start from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span>.)</p>",
        "id": 312013839,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1669296057
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition was made by Johannes Hoelzl who has a computer science background and might well know very little about what mathematicians use multivariable polynomials for. I wouldn't take the definition too seriously Antoine -- Johannes might just have come up with an arbitrary definition which happened to basically agree with the usual definition in the single variable case. Polynomials were in a very experimental state four years ago.</p>",
        "id": 312021221,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1669298215
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, so since <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"406490\">@María Inés de Frutos Fernández</span> and I are revisiting that in order to define more general weights on polynomial algebras (in order to define the the divided power algebra of a module,  we could also revise this as well. It does not seem to be much used anyway.</p>",
        "id": 312022862,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1669298675
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Jujian Zhang has made projective space in Lean but I think weighted projective space would also be a welcome addition -- perhaps not by you two, who are doing more important stuff, but please bear it in mind if you're going to make new definitions of degree :-)</p>",
        "id": 312025542,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1669299487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed…</p>",
        "id": 312036355,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1669302591
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130609\">Antoine Chambert-Loir</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Degrees.20of.20polynomials.20in.20many.20variables/near/311991887\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>From the perspective of computer algebra, I would have imagined that the degrees of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> would be either <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{x^2y,y^3\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{ (2,1), (0,3)\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{(</span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mclose\">)}</span></span></span></span>, the set of (uncoefficiented) monomials or of exponents.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is basically <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/mv_polynomial.support\">docs#mv_polynomial.support</a>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There are many degrees available, the three obvious ones are the degree with respect to xx (2 in this case), the one with respect to yy (3), or the total degree (3 as well).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/mv_polynomial.degree_of\">docs#mv_polynomial.degree_of</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/mv_polynomial.total_degree\">docs#mv_polynomial.total_degree</a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But you can assign weights to variables and you get many other, of a similar vein. <br>\nBut the lexicographic orderings, or their opposite, are also pretty much studied. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/15296\">#15296</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/16127\">#16127</a> (not yet merged) by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"321459\">@Damiano Testa</span></p>",
        "id": 312042771,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1669304665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My recollection was that there was some resistance on introducing \"degrees\" for general <code>add_monoid_algebra</code>s.  It may be quicker to define degree in the special case of <code>mv_polynomial</code>s and then worry later if/when more general notions of degrees are desired.</p>\n<p>Partially related: there is also a <code>counterexamples</code> file where there is some reasoning about \"exponent vectors\" of <code>add_monoid_algebra</code>s.  For instance <code>zero_divisors_of_periodic</code> and <code>zero_divisors_of_torsion</code> in <code>counterexamples/zero_divisors_in_add_monoid_algebras</code>.</p>",
        "id": 312050461,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1669307344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I also have other PRs open with a proof that <code>mv_polynomial</code>s only have trivial zero divisors when the base-ring does, but am not pushing them to get merged, since</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I currently do not have much time;</li>\n<li>would rather focus on the port, if/when I will have time!</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 312050810,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1669307440
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just found out that PRs <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/17855\">#17855</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/17956\">#17956</a> are now open.</p>",
        "id": 315741089,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1670997609
